# Git Commit Rules

## Absolute Prohibition on AI Attribution

When making git commits, the following rules MUST be followed without exception:

1. **NEVER add Co-authored-by lines** - Do not add any co-author attribution for Cursor, AI, or any automated agent
2. **NEVER modify git config** - Do not change user.name, user.email, or any git configuration
3. **NEVER reference AI/Cursor in commit messages** - No mention of "generated by", "assisted by", "with help from", or similar phrases referencing AI tools
4. **NEVER use trailers** - Do not add any git trailers that attribute work to AI or automated tools

## Commit Creation Method

When creating commits, use low-level git commands to bypass any automatic attribution:

```bash
# Stage changes
git add <files>

# Create commit using commit-tree to avoid hooks/automation
TREE=$(git write-tree)
PARENT=$(git rev-parse HEAD)
NEW_COMMIT=$(echo "commit message" | git commit-tree $TREE -p $PARENT)
git reset --hard $NEW_COMMIT
```

Or explicitly set environment variables:

```bash
GIT_AUTHOR_NAME="<user name>" \
GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="<user email>" \
GIT_COMMITTER_NAME="<user name>" \
GIT_COMMITTER_EMAIL="<user email>" \
git commit -m "message"
```

## Verification

After any commit, verify no AI attribution exists:

```bash
git log -1 --format=full  # Check for Co-authored-by lines
git log --format="%an <%ae>" | sort | uniq  # Verify only user appears
```

## Summary

All git history must appear as if created solely by the human user. No traces of AI assistance should exist in:
- Author/committer fields
- Co-authored-by trailers
- Commit message body
- Any other git metadata
